\begin_layout Standard
The substitution rule for Indefinite Integrals,
 if obtained directly from interpreting the Chain Rule backwards,
 reads as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Integration by Substitution
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:ibs1"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 be functions,
 and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

 is an antiderivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int f(u(x))u'(x)\,\dl x=F(u(x))+C.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve a problem using this notation,
 one must first identify what the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to be used should be,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Figuring out what the correct 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 to choose is a problem in and of itself.
 There are no easy answers here:
 To gain the skill to find a good substitution requires intuition,
 creativity,
 and above all,
 practice.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and from there what the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must be.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Suppose we are solving the integral
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\cos(x)\sqrt{\sin(x)}\,\dl x.
\]

\end_inset

In this case,
 one 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

guesses
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that we might use 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=\sin(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 the integral becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\cos(x)\sqrt{\sin(x)}\,\dl x=\int\sqrt{u(x)}u'(x)\,\dl x,
\]

\end_inset

and so we may set 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\sqrt{x}$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\cos(x)\sqrt{\sin(x)}\,\dl x=\int f(u(x))u'(x)\,\dl x,
\]

\end_inset

whence 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:ibs1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 tells us that,
 if we find an antiderivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 (a problem which needs to be separately solved,
 and in this case yields,
 for example,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)=\frac{2}{3}x^{3/2}$
\end_inset

),
 we may write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\cos(x)\sqrt{\sin(x)}\,\dl x=\int f(u(x))u'(x)\,\dl x=F(u(x))+C=\frac{2}{3}\left(\sin(x)\right)^{3/2}+C.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice,
 this notation is burdensome and difficult to work with,
 and the fact that it requires us to solve a sub-problem 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

on the side
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 makes solutions harder to write and harder to follow.
\end_layout

